Pattern 4: Sliding Window (Two-Pointer Variant)
1. The Interview Triggers
*). Working with continuous/contiguous subarrays or substrings.
*). Questions containing the words: "maximum window", "minimum length matching condition", or "longest subarray".

2. Core Mechanics
*). The right pointer expands the boundary of a dynamic sub-segment window to introduce elements. If a constraint or condition is breached, the left pointer contracts the sub-segment window from the back to restore state compliance.

3. Production Java Blueprint
public int slidingWindowTemplate(int[] nums, int target) {
    int left = 0;
    int minLength = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
    int currentSum = 0;
    
    for (int right = 0; right < nums.length; right++) {
        currentSum += nums[right]; // Expand the window
        
        // Contract the window while condition is valid
        while (currentSum >= target) {
            minLength = Math.min(minLength, right - left + 1); // Track solution
            currentSum -= nums[left]; // Drop element from left
            left++; // Shrink window
        }
    }
    return minLength == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? 0 : minLength;
}

5. Essential Interview Questions
Medium: LeetCode 209 - Minimum Size Subarray Sum, LeetCode 3 - Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
Hard: LeetCode 992 - Subarrays with K Different Integers
